title: For Sale/Trade:  FEG PA-63 Makarov 9x18. Beautiful!!
postcontent:
I've had this PA-63 for almost four years now and its time to let it go on to someone who could use it more than I. 
I purchased this because I owned a pre-ban FEG AK-47 and the PA-63 made a for a nice companion firearm for it, both being FEGs and all.. but I sold the AK two years ago.
After purchasing it I mended the heavy trigger by replacing the hammer spring with one that is just heavy enough to impact every single primer, but not so heavy to break your finger trying to pull it, such as the stock hammer spring is. 
Upon testing it, the Double action pull is 12.5-13lbs and the single action pull is 4-5lbs. The stock Double action pull was somewhere around 5 million lbs.. so changing the spring made for a great improvement.
After replacing the spring I buffed out the entire gun frame as to remove the brushed aluminum appearance and replace it with a shiny mirror finish. In the pictures it does not show any serial numbers.. They are there, I assure you. I've edited them out of the pictures. The shiny mirror finish on the frame makes this gun look amazingly beautiful. The only other thing I have done to it would be to make the sights more visible by adding white paint which is made for sights.
This gun shoots very accurately. I have only shot around 90 rounds of 9x18 from it but I can tell you that it shoots just as well as my expensive handguns due to its fixed barrel.

title: For Sale:  Impressions of the Carson Gun Show
postcontent:
Well, nobody to blame but myself.  Should have been more aware.
I purchased a brand new, in the box "Benchmade" folding knife from the nice guys at Future Edge out of Minden.  It's a really nice piece...for a COUNTERFEIT KNIFE.  The owner, Neal Sprott, was a really nice guy to talk to.  Even said that he knows some of the same people that I do.  Well, bought my new "American Made Benchmade" and headed back to the Lake.  I emailed a picture to my son, who is an a avid Benchmade collector.  All I got back was, "you got burned".  I checked against the Benchmade part number on the blade and sure enough...not the knife I bought.  I did reach out to Neal at Future Edge, by way of the email address that he gave, but unfortunately...nada.  Hope you all had a better experience.  There were some "real nice people there".
Larry

postcontent:
I have an original 1864 stamped Springfield .58 muzzle loader civil war rifle for sale.  Marked with "S.N. & W.T.C. FOR MASSACHUSETTS" on the lock plate, S. Norris and W.T. Clement of Springfield, Mass. produced approximately 11,000 of these on direct contract for the State of Massachusetts in 1863-1864. The rifle is completely intact and in really good shape.  This is the 3-band, 40" barrel version.  In fact, I recently had a gunsmith in Bend, OR inspect the barrel and verify that it can be fired using correct procedures for this weapon. There are some scuffs/scratches on the barrel where the bayonette had been fitted in the past, but I do not have the bayonette. title: For Sale:  NEW Larue Tactical 20 rd .308 magazines OBR
postcontent:
I have for sale some brand new Larue Tactical .308 mags.  Price is $100 each.  Details are below.
Some say it's the finest 7.62 mag ever developed. 
Even though these steel 7.62 mags were designed and produced as a factory magazine for the LaRue OBR 7.62 rifle, they'll fit just about any rifle that accepts M110-pattern magazines.

The cartridge guide rails along the side feature a unique horizontal-break near the feedlips. This design reduces cartridge drag as the extractor groove rides along the feedlips. The magazine seam is "hidden:" at the rear instead of being placed conventionally at the front, where it robs the magazine of precious internal capacity (very important if you intend on using handloads, or ammunition like M118LR with larger overall cartridge lengths). The seam is neatly laser-welded the entire length of the magazine to reduce build-up of grit and deposits that inhibit the magazine's ability to fall free. The slick, corrosion-resistant surface improves cartridge feeding, allows the magazine to drop free and makes cleanup and maintenance easier. 

Our followers are made of glass-reinforced polymer, designed to reduce tilt, and effortlessly feeds cartridges into the chamber with perfect alignment. They are hi-vis red, to take the guess-work out of quickly eyeballing whether your mag is empty (especially helpful in low-light conditions). 

The floor plates (also designed and manufactured in-house) keep the spring centered, and allow easy breakdown for cleaning and maintenance.
